<subSubSection id="AF76998C0513D6E36E8663AA216B637B" lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="357" pageId="31" pageNumber="354" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="E22A570D3422B5C514745920E111B871" pageId="31" pageNumber="354">Natural history</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7CFC9BDCAB9472654B2B4C045AE0A063" lastPageId="33" lastPageNumber="356" pageId="31" pageNumber="354">
All observed 
<taxonomicName id="6B5E775544E32249DDF5D8842AF93783" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="31" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda">Ancylometes</taxonomicName>
species (
<taxonomicName id="BC9043EC824B413A132172C7B322803E" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="31" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" species="bogotensis">bogotensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B0D1F6464A2EE282DC684BEDDF61BEB3" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="31" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" species="hewitsoni">hewitsoni</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="EA0B08FB6C7DDCC3CA7D56BD4B847273" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="31" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" species="riparius">riparius</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="CE4686081B92CB360154544558EB2AF9" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="31" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" species="rufus">rufus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B60998CA8B2B1BA910CF756B8AF5BD78" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="31" pageNumber="354" phylum="Arthropoda" species="terrenus">terrenus</taxonomicName>
) are nocturnal 
<pageBreakToken id="A793D1798688E24C92D0DA981B13B4D9" pageId="32" pageNumber="355" start="start">hunters</pageBreakToken>
and strongly ground related, however they climb on tree trunks to hide during inundation of the ground or to flee from army ants. During the day they hide in crevices and at night they hunt in a sit-and-wait manner, often near water bodies. The biology of 
<taxonomicName id="AB58E56451E9C9BCEA0E37E48F90CAB1" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.bestMatchDistance="29816" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="32" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" species="rufus">A. rufus</taxonomicName>
in a terra firme forest near Manaus (Reserva Ducke) was studied by Azevedo (1999). The species is most frequently observed 
<pageBreakToken id="4C68E2048D1DC974D320331648C35FB0" pageId="33" pageNumber="356" start="start">along</pageBreakToken>
small rivers in the forest. An observed strong temporal variation of densities along the stream indicated seasonal migrations within the habitat, e.g. to the stream banks during the dry season and to small water ponds within the forest during the wet season.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="65F74E7620AD5DB4C6DD9CB9E70C5B6D" pageId="33" pageNumber="356">
Hunting on frogs has repeatedly been observed for several species (
<normalizedToken id="C9F1D55F4018635558BC7D50732D361D" originalValue="Brandão" pageId="33" pageNumber="356">Brandao</normalizedToken>
pers. comm. for 
<taxonomicName id="BF5ED3027495C29AE35F98390B6561C4" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.bestMatchDistance="28981" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="33" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda" species="concolor">A. concolor</taxonomicName>
- IBSP 6536, preying Hyla sp.; for 
<taxonomicName id="538F10DC6A8EB214E9A7B14031C75980" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.bestMatchDistance="29975" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="33" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda" species="rufus">A. rufus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E5C4464902594905AF54D0DFAB93A04F" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.bestMatchDistance="16992" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="33" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda" species="hewitsoni">A. hewitsoni</taxonomicName>
pers. obs. and photo in 
<normalizedToken id="796F4A5EE8E2D05022A5CC0029D5E3E2" originalValue="Höfer" pageId="33" pageNumber="356">Hoefer</normalizedToken>
&amp; Beck 1996, photos in Bernarde et al. 1999, 
<normalizedToken id="CAAD1F5FE287E5B4C2A1929A71353325" originalValue="Hödl" pageId="33" pageNumber="356">Hoedl</normalizedToken>
1993); and tadpoles (pers. obs.) and fish (pers. obs.) are also preyed. The spiders can easily paddle on the water surface, and dive for prey but also to hide; remaining more than 30 minutes below water has been recorded (pers. obs.). One bite accident in Manaus has been brought to our knowledge, but in the field these spiders are not at all aggressive and can easily be captured by hand. Moults are often found hanging down from leaves in vegetation (30-50 cm above ground). One male which was kept for one night in a small device had difficulties to moult, which resulted in curved legs. Pompilid wasps have been observed to prey on 
<taxonomicName id="2D4D02219AC0DF90EE60ABB67AE3F420" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="33" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda">Ancylometes</taxonomicName>
spiders. To avoid flooding in inundation forests and army ant raids in terra firme forest the spiders climb on tree trunks, where they were caught in arboreal funnel traps.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BDC4BC0B7A723396E004F6D29D92A28D" lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="357" pageId="33" pageNumber="356">
Mating of 
<taxonomicName id="6C86BFE4F695CA8C60485C1AD7CA4932" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.bestMatchDistance="1766" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="33" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda" species="bogotensis">A. bogotensis</taxonomicName>
was described by Merrett (1988). We found some females with their epigynes plugged. Females carry their egg sacs, which are covered by strong brown water proof silk, attached to the chelicerae and held by the pedipalps under the venter. Egg sacs of 
<taxonomicName id="A41DF85B89082D6C428574AC1D4FCDD6" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.bestMatchDistance="30230" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="33" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda" species="rufus">A. rufus</taxonomicName>
contained more than 1000 eggs. The nursery webs constructed by the females of 
<taxonomicName id="AB89FD8A8AE9538F8F39D1FE36DF8D0C" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" genus.bestMatchDistance="30247" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="33" pageNumber="356" phylum="Arthropoda" species="rufus">A. rufus</taxonomicName>
are about 
<pageBreakToken id="89B3310FBAB4BCD495CE4D99C9BE0016" pageId="34" pageNumber="357" start="start">10</pageBreakToken>
cm in diameter and were frequently encountered near the ground along the stream. Juveniles were observed to remain for about one week in the webs. Adults were encountered throughout the year indicating that there is no seasonal reproduction(Azevedo 1999).
</paragraph>
